<Rewrite PAsource="" >AN ANGRY </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >worker </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >put glass in</Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" > thousands of savoury pancakes </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >after </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >being </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >told </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >he was to be made redundant, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >a court heard </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >yesterday.</Rewrite>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >John McKay, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >61, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >is said to have </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >poured 19 handfuls of glass into diced onions, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >which </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >were added to the snacks at the Findus factory in Newcastle upon Tyne.

A massive recall was launched in February </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >last year </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >after customers suffered cuts to their mouths and broken teeth after biting into the pancakes. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Millions of </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >the snacks had to be returned, costing </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >the </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >firm </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >£3.5million, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >a jury </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >heard.</Verbatim>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >Paul Sloan, prosecuting, told Newcastle </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Crown </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Court </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >that </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >McKay was heard singing: </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >"Findus pancakes are class, because they are full of glass" </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >by colleagues at the Nestle-owned plant, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >which employs 800 workers.</Verbatim>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >The contamination </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >alert </Rewrite>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >came after </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >a round of job losses </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >was announced. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >McKay was told he was third on the list </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >to go, </Rewrite>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >following </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >the "last-in, first-out" policy. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >He had worked at the plant for five years.</Verbatim>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >Mr Sloan told the jury: </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >"The defendant was heard by colleagues saying he was unhappy with his redundancy."

"He was seen with cuts to his fingers and told </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >them </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >he had cut himself clearing a greenhouse, an explanation he later denied giving."

"On the weekend of January 10 and 11, he was heard to say, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >'If someone wanted to get back at the company it would be easy, because the machinery does not detect'"

"On the weekend of January 24 and 25, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >he was seen loitering around the chilled store area. The following weekend </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >he </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >was off sick - </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >and no pancakes were contaminated. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >All the other </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >staff </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >facing redundancy were at work." </Verbatim>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >McKay, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >of </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Wark, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Northumberland, </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >denies five charges of contaminating </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >food.</Rewrite>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >The trial </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >continues.</Rewrite>


